## Diagnosis

The `micro` rendering mode kicks in when a tile falls into the 32–64 px width bucket and renders category names at 8 px. 8 px text is below the WCAG minimum readable threshold and is effectively invisible to most users. The tile is communicating "I exist" while communicating nothing useful — which is worse than silence.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-072 — Graceful-degradation theatre**: the component adds progressively smaller text modes to *appear* to handle constrained space, but the smallest mode produces output that is functionally illegible. The fix is not a smaller font — it's **no text at all** (or a tooltip/title attribute only), letting the visual encoding (color, position) carry the meaning at that scale.

The secondary issue is that the size-bucket thresholds are baked inline with the render logic, coupling layout math to typography decisions in a single conditional chain.

---

## Fix

### 1. Remove the `micro` text mode; replace with title-only fallback

```tsx
// components/KnowledgeTreemap/KnowledgeTreemap.tsx  (or .jsx)

// ─── BEFORE ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
type TileMode = 'full' | 'compact' | 'micro'

function getTileMode(width: number, height: number): TileMode {
  if (width < 64 || height < 32) return 'micro'    // ← produces 8 px text
  if (width < 120 || height < 56) return 'compact'
  return 'full'
}

// inside the tile render:
{mode === 'micro'   && <span className="text-[8px] leading-none truncate">{name}</span>}
{mode === 'compact' && <span className="text-xs   leading-tight truncate">{name}</span>}
{mode === 'full'    && <span className="text-sm   leading-snug"          >{name}</span>}
```

```tsx
// ─── AFTER ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
type TileMode = 'full' | 'compact' | 'silent'   // micro → silent

function getTileMode(width: number, height: number): TileMode {
  if (width < 64 || height < 32) return 'silent'   // too small to label
  if (width < 120 || height < 56) return 'compact'
  return 'full'
}
```

### 2. Update the tile render to suppress text in `silent` mode

```tsx
// components/KnowledgeTreemap/TreemapTile.tsx

interface TreemapTileProps {
  name: string
  value: number
  color: string
  width: number
  height: number
}

export function TreemapTile({ name, value, color, width, height }: TreemapTileProps) {
  const mode = getTileMode(width, height)

  return (
    <div
      className="relative overflow-hidden rounded-[2px] transition-opacity hover:opacity-90"
      style={{ width, height, backgroundColor: color }}
      // Always expose the name to assistive tech & browser tooltip
      title={name}
      aria-label={`${name}: ${value}`}
      role="img"
    >
      {mode === 'compact' && (
        <span className="absolute inset-x-1 top-1 text-xs leading-tight truncate font-medium text-white/90 drop-shadow-sm select-none">
          {name}
        </span>
      )}

      {mode === 'full' && (
        <span className="absolute inset-x-2 top-2 text-sm leading-snug font-medium text-white drop-shadow-sm select-none">
          {name}
        </span>
      )}

      {/* mode === 'silent': no text rendered; title attr carries the label */}
    </div>
  )
}
```

### 3. (Optional but recommended) Wire a tooltip for `silent` tiles

If you use Radix UI or a similar primitive:

```tsx
// Only add Tooltip overhead for tiles that can't self-label
{mode === 'silent' ? (
  <Tooltip.Provider delayDuration={300}>
    <Tooltip.Root>
      <Tooltip.Trigger asChild>
        <div {/* …tile div props… */} />
      </Tooltip.Trigger>
      <Tooltip.Portal>
        <Tooltip.Content className="rounded bg-gray-900 px-2 py-1 text-xs text-white shadow-md">
          {name}
          <Tooltip.Arrow className="fill-gray-900" />
        </Tooltip.Content>
      </Tooltip.Portal>
    </Tooltip.Root>
  </Tooltip.Provider>
) : (
  <div {/* …tile div props with inline label… */} />
)}
```

---

## Principle

> **Never render text below your system's minimum legible size. If a container is too small to hold readable text, render no text — not smaller text.**

Concretely:

- Establish a **single minimum font size token** in your design system (e.g., `--text-min: 0.75rem / 12px`) and treat it as a floor, not a starting point for further shrinking.
- When content cannot fit at the minimum size, the correct response is **omission + an accessible fallback** (`title`, `aria-label`, tooltip-on-hover) — not compression.
- Size-bucket logic belongs in one place (`getTileMode` or equivalent). Typography decisions must not be re-derived inside render JSX; they should consume the mode token and map it to a pre-defined text style, making it impossible to accidentally introduce a new sub-minimum size.

This keeps illegible states structurally impossible rather than just conventionally avoided.
